                                \addplot[primarycurve,-{Kite}] coordinates {(0,0) (4,5) (12,-5)};
                                \addplot[only marks] coordinates{(0,0)};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                <p>After a little bit of work, Khenbish was able to come up with a formula for the light's path: <me>p(x)=5-\frac{5}{4}\abs{x-4}</me> where <m>p(x)</m> stands for the position, in <quantity><unit base="foot" /></quantity>, above (for positive values) or below (for negatives) the center line through his room that represents the <m>x</m>-axis, where <m>x</m> is also measured in <quantity><unit base="foot" /></quantity>. Use technology and a graph of this formula to answer the following questions.<ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>Khenbish's room is <quantity><mag>10</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity> wide according to <xref ref="figure-laser-pointer">Figure</xref> (in the vertical direction in the figure). What is the room's length (in the horizontal direction in the figure)?</p></li>
                    <li><p>How far along the wall is the mirror centered?</p></li>
                    <li><p>If you stood <quantity><mag>9</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity> from the left wall, how far above or below the room's center line (<m>x</m>-axis) should you stand to have the laser pointer hit you?</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                    <figure xml:id="figure-laser-pointer-detail">
                    <caption>Detailed Birds-Eye View of Khenbish's Room</caption>
                        <image width="47%">
                            <description>A Cartesian graph with the graph of y=5-5/4*abs(x-4), which looks like an upside down V with the vertex of the V at the point (4,5). The graph starts at the origin with a solid dot. The right side extends as a line with slope -5/4 with an arrow at (12,-5) and the left side extends with slope 5/4. There is a rectangle drawn with corners (0,-5), (0,5), (12,5), and (12,-5) representing the walls of the room. There are small rectangles near the origin representing the window sill and at the point (4,5) representing the mirror.</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,xmax=13,ymin=-6,ymax=6,    xtick={0,1,...,12}, ytick={-5,-4,...,5}, minor ytick={-4,-2,...,4}, grid]
                                \addplot[color=secondcolor] coordinates{(0,-5)(0,5)(12,5)(12,-5)(0,-5)};
                                \addplot[fill=brown!20!white] coordinates{(0,-1)(0.2,-1)(0.2,1)(0,1)(0,-1)};
                                \addplot[fill=black!20!white] coordinates{(3.5,5)(3.5,4.95)(4.5,4.95)(4.5,5)(3.5,5)};
                                \addplot[primarycurve,-{Kite}] coordinates {(0,0) (4,5) (12,-5)};
                                \addplot[only marks] coordinates{(0,0)};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>

                    <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>To find the room's length, first note that since the laser hits the corner of the room, the <m>x</m> coordinate of the lasers position would tell us the room's width. According to the detailed graph, the <m>x</m>-coordinate when <m>y=-5</m> is <m>12</m>. So the room must be <m>12</m> feet wide.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The mirror is centered exactly where the laser hits the wall. This is the vertex of the absolute value graph which, according to the graph, is at the point <m>(4,5)</m>. This tells us that the mirror is centered <m>4</m> feet from the left wall.</p></li>
                    <li><p>If you are standing 9 feet from the left wall, the laser's position will be a bit more than one foot behind the rooms center line, by the diagram. While technology can tell us the exact answer, here is how to do this problem algebraically.</p>
                    <p><md>
                        <mrow>d(\highlight{9})\amp=5-\frac{5}{4}\abs{\highlight{9}-4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=5-\frac{5}{4}\abs{5}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=5-\frac{5}{4}\cdot 5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=5-\frac{25}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=5-6.25</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-1.25</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                    <p>So, it looks like if you stand <m>9</m> feet from the left wall, you need to stand <m>1.25</m> feet behind the center line (which would be <m>6.25</m> feet from the wall with the mirror on it) to be hit by the laser.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Absolute value functions are also used when a value must be within a certain distance or tolerance. For example, a person's body temperature is considered <q>normal</q> if it is within <m>0.5</m> degrees of <quantity><mag>98.6</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, so their temperature could be up to <m>0.5</m> degrees less than or greater than that temperature. To be within normal range, the difference between the two values must be less than or equal to <m>0.5</m>, and it does not matter whether it is positive or negative. We will introduce a function for measuring this in the next example.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The function <m>D</m> defined by <m>D(T)=\abs{T-98.6}</m> represents the difference between a person's temperature, T, in Fahrenheit, and <quantity><mag>98.6</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>. A person's temperature is considered <q>normal</q> if <m>D(T)</m> is less than or equal to <m>0.5</m>. Use <m>D(T)</m> to evaluate each person's temperature.<ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>98.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, is that within normal range?</p></li>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>99.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, is that within normal range?</p></li>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>97.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, is that within normal range?</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>98.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, then we have:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>D(\highlight{98.3})\amp=\abs{\highlight{98.3}-98.6}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{-0.3}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=0.3</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                        <p>Since the value of <m>D(98.3)</m> is a number smaller than <m>0.5</m>, then <quantity><mag>98.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity> must be within normal range.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>99.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, then we have:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>D(\highlight{99.3})\amp=\abs{\highlight{99.3}-98.6}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{0.7}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=0.7</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                        <p>Since the value of <m>D(99.3)</m> is a number bigger than <m>0.5</m>, then <quantity><mag>99.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity> must <em>not</em> be within normal range.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>If a person has a temperature of <quantity><mag>97.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity>, then we have:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>D(\highlight{97.3})\amp=\abs{\highlight{97.3}-98.6}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\abs{-1.3}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=1.3</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                        <p>Since the value of <m>D(97.3)</m> is a number bigger than <m>0.5</m>, then <quantity><mag>97.3</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity> must <em>not</em> be within normal range.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The entryway to the Louvre Museum in Paris is through I.<nbsp/>M.<nbsp/>Pei's metal and glass Louvre Pyramid. This pyramid has a square base and is <m>71</m> feet high and <m>112</m> feet wide. The formula <m>h(x)=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{x-56}</m> gives the height above ground level of the pyramid at a distance of <m>x</m> from the left side of the pyramid base.</p>
                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="2%">
                    <figure xml:id="figure-Louvre-Pyramid">
                    <caption>A Diagram of the Front of the Louvre Pyramid</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>A Cartesian graph with the graph of y=71-71/56*abs(x-56), which looks like an upside down V with the vertex of the V at the point (56,71). The graph exists between x=0 and x=112. The right side extends as a line with slope -71/56 and the left side extends with slope 71/56.</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-10,
                                                xmax=120,
                                                ymin=-10,
                                                ymax=80,
                                                xtick={0,20,...,100},
                                                minor xtick={0,10,...,110},
                                                ytick={0,10,...,70},
                                                minor ytick={0,5,...,75},
                                                grid=none]
                                        \addplot[-, thick, color=fifthcolor] coordinates {(0,0) (56,71) (112,0)};
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>

                    <p><ol label="a.">
                        <li><p>If you are <m>20</m> feet from the left edge, how high will the pyramid rise in front of you? Round your result to the nearest tenth of an inch.</p></li>
                        <li><p>How far from the left edge is the center of the pyramid?</p></li>
                        <li><p>Using your previous answer, check that the formula gives you the correct height at the center.</p></li>
                    </ol></p>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>If you are <m>20</m> feet from the left edge, then <m>x</m> is <m>20</m>. Substituting <m>20</m> for <m>x</m> we have<md>
                            <mrow>h(\substitute{20})\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{\substitute{20}-56}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{-36}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\cdot 36</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp\approx 71-45.643</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp\approx 25.357</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp\approx 25.4</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    <p>The pyramid is about <m>25.4</m> feet high at the position <m>20</m> feet from the left edge.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The center of the pyramid is <m>56</m> feet from the either edge since it's half of <m>112</m> feet.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Putting <m>x=56</m> into the formula for <m>h</m> gives us<md>
                             <mrow>h(\substitute{56})\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{\substitute{56}-56}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\abs{0}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71-\frac{71}{56}\cdot 0</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=71</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    <p>And so the formula does give us the correct maximum height of <m>71</m> feet at the center of the pyramid.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

